value.0: A skilled warrior from Luskan's Keeper's Bane.
These helms are crafted for the followers of House Shadowflame
Said to be constructed of discarded dragon scales and forged my master smiths, this armor is powerful and heavily protective of the loyal soldier within.

This burning longsword carries the crest of House Shadowflame on the hilt, it's blade seeming to sing as it is swung through the air.  Inspection of the weapon will find it in good upkeep, but with signs of near constant use; a sure indication that this is a trustworthy weapon that has seen much action.

This shield is commonly mass produced during times of war to protect valuable field officers. Sometimes they gather in merchants inventories during periods of peace or when a surplus has been made. They are definitely more practical than elaborate, a fairly straight-forward protection.
A wolf-hide cloak of excellent quality and craftsmanship.

Caster Level(s):  Assassin 1
Innate Level:  1
School:  Conjuration
Descriptor(s):  Obscuring Mist
Component(s):  Verbal, Somatic
Range:  Touch
Area of Effect / Target: Single
Duration:  1 Turn / Level
Additional Counter Spells:  
Save:  Harmless
Spell Resistance:  No

A misty vapor arises around the caster, granting a 20% cover bonus from all attacks.

OOC Requirement: 11 Intelligence, and 2 Assassin levels.
Soft silky robes woven of darkness and shadow stuff.

Medium chainmail armor often worn by House Shadowflame Archers and scouts, it sacrifices the weight of armor on the upper body on the right side in favor of heavier armor on the left, as most archers stand with their left towards the enemy.  This interesting concept has allowed this particular design to affort slightly more protection from arrows, though it is protective from little else in reality.
Created in great quantities by long forgotten mages, these weapons were apparently designed for sell or outfitting of armies.
Created in great quantities by long forgotten mages, these weapons were apparently designed for sell or outfitting of armies.

Once worn, this cloak is seen to have many beneficial enhancements.  Yet with continuous use, the negative side-effects become quite apparent.  

Social apathy is first, with the user slowly becoming more distanced from friends and peers.  

Next, comes the single mindedness of the kill.  The Assassin gradually loses her cold professionalism slightly, in her single pursuit of the job.  

Some have been known to get sloppy when using this robe on assignments, but often it is taken with gratitude when weighed against it's usefulness against the target, especially against clerics.

This masterful set of plate armor is made of fine steel. However, thats not all there is to it: The breastplate is, in fact, formed by several matt black dragon scales, and the thighs, shins and shoulders are all enforced with sheets of similar, but smaller, scales. The scales are moist with a foul-smelling substance. Armors of this type are manufactured by several smiths in Faern, and its not uncommon for dragonslayers to seek one such craftsman in order to wear their defeated foe in a stylish and useful fashion.

Iron plated greaves forged for the most determined of dwarven warriors with the Dark Spire. Their warriors would wear these heavily enchanted pieces of armor, and become near unbeatable. Unfortunately, all but a small few of these were lost when the giants of fire and ice overtook the mountain.

Regardless of the defeat of the dwarves long ago, these boots still retain their durability and ability to retain a blow, just as their previous owners.
The great emblem of the Dragon sits astride each bracer, empowered with might and energy.
Forged in the magical workshop at House Shadowflame, this sword was designed for hunting fire giants, a favored prey of this house.

This cloak of unliving skin provides a minor protection against negative energy and arrows sink harmlessly into it's icky skin. The cold, sickly skin also writhes against your own skin, which gives you a rather creepy aspect.
A ring especially made to strengthen all attributes of the body.
This amulet has several transparent, blue circles spinning around the gem's center. It reacts quickly to certain types of weapons and damages and provides a small defense.

A belt designed to emulate a type of warrior called a berserker; fearless, quick and brutal, but the rage they enter also works against them, clouding their thoughts with bloodlust, making even the most logical of thoughts a difficult task.

Of incredible rarity and made from exquisite materials, these helmets are a set of six, all designed to enhance one particular part of its wearer's strengths.

The elusive nature of its seller mark these as an oddity without history or origin, but old tombs and remains in the Amian region are sometimes found to be in possession of them, suggesting that they were used even in ancient times.

------------------------------------------------------
Standard Rage
------------------------------------------------------
This is the normal Barbarian Rage.   

+1 Attack per 4 Barbarian levels, capped at +6.
+1 Damage per 4 Barbarian levels, capped at +5.
+1 Will saves per 8 Barbarian levels, capped at +3.
+1 Fortitude save per 8 Barbarian levels, capped at +3.
+2 Hit Points per Barbarian level.
Penalized -2 to Armor Class. This is voided at Barbarian level 17 and above.


-------------------------------------------------------
Unyielding Rage
-------------------------------------------------------
A focused Barbarian rage that channels their fury into raw speed, ignoring wounds as they blitz around the battlefield. 
[OOC: Available at Level 10 barbarian.] 

+1 Regeneration per 4 Barbarian levels.
+1 Dodge AC per 6 Barbarian levels, capped at +4 AC.
+1 Fortitude save per 8 Barbarian levels, capped at +3.
+1 Will save per 8 Barbarian levels, capped at +3.
+1 Reflex save per 8 Barbarian levels, capped at +3.
+3 Hit Points per Barbarian level.
+1 AB per 8 Barbarian levels, capped at +3.


-------------------------------------------------------
Ferocity Attack
-------------------------------------------------------
A focused Barbarian rage that sends the barbarian into a true frenzy of whipping blades and destructive might. The price for pure offense however, is a lack of defense. 
[OOC: Available at Level 15 barbarian.]

+1 Attack Per Round, stacks with Haste.
+2 Damage per 4 Barbarian levels, capped at +12.
+1 Fortitude save per 8 Barbarian levels, capped at +3.
50% percent move speed increase, doesn't stack with Haste.
-4 penalty to Dodge Armor Class.
 +1 Hit Point per Barbarian level.


-------------------------------------------------------
Thundering and Terrifying Rage
-------------------------------------------------------
The effects are added to the rage you selected above (if you have the feats, of course).


Note that there is a one turn cooldown after raging before you may do so again.
An egg-shaped onyx stone. It appears to be nothing magical or out of the ordinary...

A death tyrant was the result of a beholder's mad dreams of existing beyond death. On the rare occasion in which such dreams took hold of a live beholder, its flesh rotted away, and a naked skull with spectral points of red light for eyes would emerge. A death tyrant held much of the powers of the original beholder, now fueled by the power of Undeath.
Smaller then most Elder Orbs, Galthdruksh learn to use it's size as an advantage.

A supernatural aura of dread hangs thickly in the air around this malignant black figure. It looks something like a gargoyle, with large shadowy wings, curling horns, and a lashing tail. Its body appears to be sculpted from purest night, and its face is blank, except for the pale, lifeless orbs of its eyes.
A creature that preyed upon feelings of grief and loss. Though they resembled undead demons, they were in fact manifestations of the Shadowfell and fragments of death incarnate.

These gloves were woven from spider silk and embedded atop the back of each glove is an amethyst, one purple and the other green. The amethysts each feature conjoined runes of conjuration and divination carved into them. On both index and ring fingers are open-ended adamantine thimbles.

Weaved through the gloves is the hair of a drow, forming an unusual and disjointed web-like pattern. This arrangement may appear innocuous at first, but a closer inspection reveals that they are in fact an array of drow runes that have been weaved together in a strange interplay with each other. When in the presence of faerzress, the web pattern would begin to glow alternating colours of purple and green, though this would only be apparent to those with Darkvision.

In essence the gloves draw in magical energies, specifically that of faerzress, which are then broken down to boost the wearer's comprehension of spellcraft and its linkages with faerzress, thus enabling greater control in the manipulation of faerzress as well as feeding the energies into the body, boosting the wearer's vitality.
